Exam 1 - OLS and heteroskedasticity

Look at the following model for bank employees wage: \[log(salary)=\beta_0+\beta_1educ+\beta_2log(salbegin)+\beta_3male+\beta_4 minority+u\] where salary is yearly wage (in 1000 US dollars), educ is education measured in number of years, salbegin is the starting salary (in 1000 US dollars) for the persons first position in the same bank, male is a dummy variable for gender, minority is one dummy variable indicating whether one belongs to a minority.

1 - Estimate the model using OLS. Comment on the output and interpret the results

options(scipen = 999)
library(readr)
data1 <- read_csv("data1.csv")
## Rows: 474 Columns: 10
##  Column specification 
## Delimiter: ","
## dbl (10): obs, idnumber, salary, lsalary, educ, salbegin, lsalbegin, male, m...
## 
##  Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
##  Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
model <- lm(salary ~ educ + log(salbegin) + male + minority, data = data1)
summary(model)

2 - Perform graphical model checking.

plot(model)

3 - Test for heteroskedasticity using the Breusch-Pagan test and the special edition of the White test.

r=residuals(model)
res = r^2
summary(lm(res~educ + log(salbegin) + male + minority, data = data1))
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = res ~ educ + log(salbegin) + male + minority, data = data1)
## 
## Residuals:

## -246.53  -48.31  -19.83    9.89 1974.48 
##

## minority        -7.020     19.966  -0.352         0.725    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 173.3 on 469 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1231, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1156 
## F-statistic: 16.46 on 4 and 469 DF,  p-value: 0.000000000001246

Because the p-value is under 0.05 we reject the null hypothesis meaning that there is heteroskedasticity in the model.

We can now calculate the LM test, where we have 474 observations and \(R^2=0.1231\):

LM = 0.1231*474
LM
## [1] 58.3494

We can then calculate the p-value of chi-square \(\chi^2_k\):

1-pchisq(LM,4)
## [1] 0.000000000006445178
library(lmtest)
